            "Type": 0,
            "Data": "The Dream of Space",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 1,
            "Data": "For generations we have been gazing up to the stars, telling tales of the ancient constellations that made up the night sky. These fixed sources of distant light, some millions of light years away, have been the basis for navigators across the world for centuries. Mesmerized by the unknowns and vastness of space, philosophers and scientists have dedicated lifetimes of work to answer its existence.\r\n\r\nRecent developments in engineering, technology and research have unlocked the possibilities of answering many of the things that once were just a dream: Travelling to space.",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 0,
            "Data": "Rockets",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 1,
            "Data": "Modified intercontinental ballistic missiles can be used to launch artificial satellites to space. On 4 October 1957 the Soviet Union (USSR) successfully launched a satellite named Sputnik 1 into orbit around Earth, becoming the first artificial Earth satellite. It was a simple and lightweight satellite containing a radio transmitter. It transmitted a signal for three weeks before its batteries died, and reentered and burned up in the atmosphere two months later.",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 2,
            "Data": "Sputnik_asm.png",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 1,
            "Data": "Surprised by this, the United States (US) created what would become NASA to expedite the US space exploration efforts. Explorer 1 was successfully launched on January 31, 1958 on a Juno launch vehicle. A Cosmic Ray sensor onboard was used to, for the first time, detect the Van Allen belt. It provided data for almost four months before the batteries died, but remained in orbit for about 12 years before reentering the atmosphere.",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 2,
            "Data": "explorer1.png",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 0,
            "Data": "The Space Race",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 1,
            "Data": "With the launch of Sputnik 1, the competition of achieving firsts in space flight capabilities between the USSR and the US had started. The US was lagging behind, and crewed spaceflight became the next goal.",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 0,
            "Data": "Project Mercury",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 1,
            "Data": "Project Mercury is the first official space program with a target of putting a man in orbit with a safe return. After a long selection process with brutal tests, you finally received the phone call congratulating you for being selected as one of the astronauts to fly the Mercury capsule. Your comrade Patrick (\"Rad\") from the Test Pilot squadron also made it to the team.\r\n",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 0,
            "Data": "The Spacecraft",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 1,
            "Data": "The Mercury spacecraft consists of a pressurized crew compartment with room for one astronaut (1), the retropack used to return from orbit (2), a heatshield used to survive an entry through the atmosphere (3), a recovery compartment where the landing chutes are located (4), an antenna section used for communication, scanners for spacecraft orientation (5), and a launch escape system used to safely take the capsule away from a failing launch vehicle during an abort(6).",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 2,
            "Data": "theSpacecraft.png",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 0,
            "Data": "The Academy",
            "Value": 0
        },
        {
            "Type": 1,
            "Data": "The first requirement of this campaign is that you complete the Mercury Academy. The Academy can be found on the Main Menu, and will take you through all the details required to operate this brand new spaceship! During your stay with the Academy, it's recommended to also have a copy of the Reentry Mercury Flight Manual with you so you can get a deeper understanding of the systems practised during training.\r\n\r\nOptional: Once you have completed and received the Mercury Pilot Certificate, let your fellow astronauts know in the Official Reentry Discord group, where many of the other Reentry Astronauts hang out. You can find them in discord.gg/reentrygame.",
            "Value": 0
        }
    ],
